    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the confusion earlier; I was trying to be creative with a metaphor, but I made a mistake by implying the reaction is \"goblin's favorite party\" when it's actually a complex chemical dance between amino acids and reducing sugars.\n\nTo answer your question about the science: The Maillard reaction occurs when an amino group (from proteins) attacks the carbonyl group (from sugars) to form a Schiff base, which then rearranges into an amadori or ahel base. These intermediates undergo dehydration, Strecker degradation, and fragmentation, eventually forming volatile flavor compounds and melanoidins (the brown pigments).\n\nThis process is distinct from caramelization because it involves nitrogen-containing compounds, whereas caramelization is purely the pyrolysis of sugars. The temperature range you mentioned (140°C–165°C) is where these molecular collisions become frequent enough to overcome the activation energy barrier and proceed rapidly.\n\nIf you are looking for a deeper dive into the specific reaction pathways or the role of pH in accelerating this process, feel free to ask, and I can explain it without any further unnecessary metaphors.",
